[normal]Written evidence submitted by BBC Media Action
[normal]Executive Summary: [bold]This paper
[normal] is 
[normal]written 
[normal]in response to the
[normal] 
[normal]decision by the 
[normal]International 
[normal]Development 
[normal]Committee
[normal] of the UK 
[normal]Parliament
[normal] to undertake an inquiry into DFID’s work in the Middle East
[normal] and specifically “the 
[normal]effectiveness of DFID’s programme in the Occupied Palestinian Territories.” 
[normal]Th
[normal]e p
[normal]aper concentrates on BBC Media Action’s experiences in the Occupied Palestinian
[normal] Territories where
[normal] 
[normal]we have 
[normal]been working since November 2011 
[normal]funded by 
[normal]DFID through a 5
[normal]-
[normal]year accountable grant, termed the Global Grant, through DFID’
[normal]s Policy Division in London
[normal]. In addition Media Action has, 
[normal]since April 2013
[normal], been 
[normal]an implementing partner 
[normal]in a
[normal] 
[normal]contract
[normal] won
[normal] by the British Council under 
[normal]a 
[normal]DFID Framework Tender
[normal] entitled
[normal] 
[normal]‘Supporting Stability and Promoting Democracy in the Occupied Territories
[normal].”
[normal] The central argument of this submission is that media plays a key part in the lives of Palestinians
[normal] and that as a result, 
[normal]high quality and editorially robust 
[normal]programmes tha
[normal]t 
[normal]a
[normal]llow a cross-
[normal]section of Palestinian society to hold leaders to account
[normal] are central to the OPT’s future democratic development.
[normal] In particular, 
[normal]o
[normal]nline and social media are powerful 
[normal]tools for connecting communities which are divided both geographically and politically (West Bank, the Gaza strip
[normal], the diaspora
[normal]), 
[normal]as well as e
[normal]ssential mobili
[normal]s
[normal]ation tools for Palestinian youth
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Background[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
